<P>"Alas, &s;ir! you remember, then, a mo&s;t beautiful and excel|lent lady. She de&s;erved a better fate."</P>
<P>Tears &s;tood in St. Aubert's eyes; "Enough" &s;aid he, in a voice almo&s;t &s;tifled by the violence of his emotions,&mdash;"it is enough, my friend."</P>
<P>Emily though extremely &s;urpri&s;ed by her father's manner, for|bore to expre&s;s her feelings by any que&s;tion. La Voi&s;in began to apologize, but St. Aubert interrupted him; "Apology is quite unnece&s;&s;ary," &s;aid he, "let us change the topic. You was &s;peaking of the mu&s;ic we ju&s;t now h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ard."</P>
<P>"I was, mon&s;ieur&mdash;but hark!&mdash;it comes again; li&s;ten to that voice!" They were all &s;ilent;
