<P>Want of breath compelled Madame Montoni to &s;top. If any thing could have made Emily &s;mile in the&s;e moments, it would have been this &s;peech of her aunt, delivered in a voice very lit|tle below a &s;cream, and with a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of ge&s;ticulation and of countenance, that turned the whole <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> burle&s;que. Emily &s;aw, that her misfortunes did not admit of real con&s;olation, and con|temning the common place terms of &s;uperficial comfort, &s;he was &s;ilent; while Madame Montoni, jealous of her own con&s;equence, mi&s;took this for the &s;ilence of indifference, or of contempt, and reproached her with want of duty and feeling.</P>
