"I would a&s;k," &s;aid Emily, in a gentle but agitated voice, "the meaning of your words; but I perceive, that the que&s;tion would di&s;tre&s;s you now. Let us talk on other &s;ubjects. To morrow, perhaps, you may be more compo&s;ed. Ob&s;erve tho&s;e moonlight woods, and the towers, which appear ob&s;curely in the per&s;pective. You u&s;ed to be a great admirer of land&s;cape, and I have heard you &s;ay, that the faculty of deriving con&s;olation, under misfortune, from the &s;ublime pro&s;pects, which neither op|pre&s;&s;ion, or poverty withhold from us, was the peculiar ble&s;&s;ing of the innocent." Valancourt was deeply affected. "Yes," replied he, "I had once a ta&s;te for innocent and elegant delights, I had once an uncorrupted heart." Then, checking him&s;elf, he added, "Do you remember our journey together in the Pyre|nees?"</P>
<P>"Can I forget it?" &s;aid Emily&mdash;"Would that I could!" he replied;&mdash;"that was the happie&s;t period of my life. I then loved with enthu&s;ia&s;m, whatever was truely great, or good." It was &s;ometime before Emily could repre&s;s her tears, and try to command her emotions. "If you wi&s;h to forget that journey," &s;aid &s;he, "it mu&s;t certainly be my wi&s;h to forget it al&s;o." She pau&s;ed, and then added, "You make me very unea&s;y; but this is not the time for further inquiry; yet, how can I bear to be|lieve, even for a moment, that you are le&s;s worthy of my e&s;teem than formerly? I have &s;till &s;ufficient confidence in your can|dour, to believe, that, when I &s;hall a&s;k for an explanation, you will give it me."&mdash;"Yes," &s;aid Valancourt, "yes, Emily: I have not, yet lo&s;t my candour: if I had, I could better have di&s;|gui&s;ed my emotions, on learning what were your &s;ufferings&mdash;your virtues,&mdash;while I&mdash;I&mdash;but I will &s;ay no more. I did not mean to have &s;aid even &s;o much&mdash;I have been &s;urpri&s;ed into the &s;elf-accu&s;ation. Tell me, Emily, that you will not forget that jour|ney&mdash;will not wi&s;h to forget it, and I will be calm. I would not lo&s;e the remembrance of it for the whole earth."</P>
